04717nam a22006975i 9780226739496DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020026469  a97802267394967 a10.7208/97802267394962doi  a(DE-B1597)573122  a(OCoLC)1229926202  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN56.T45bR39 2021 4aHV6431b.R393 2021 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a303.6/25012231 aRaza Kolb, Anjuli Fatima, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEpidemic Empire :bColonialism, Contagion, and Terror, 1817-2020 /cAnjuli Fatima Raza Kolb. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b24 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tPreface: Politics and Scholarship in a Time of Pandemic -- tIntroduction: "Islam," Terrorism, and the Epidemic Imaginary -- tPart I. The disease poetics of empire -- t1. Great Games -- t2. The Blue Plague -- t3. Circulatory Logic -- tPart II. The body allegorical in french Algeria -- t4. The Brown Plague -- t5. Algeria Ungowned -- tPart III. Viral diaspora and global security -- t6. Selfi stan -- t7. Cures from Within -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTerrorism is a cancer, an infection, an epidemic, a plague. For more than a century, this metaphor has figured insurgent violence as contagion in order to contain its political energies. In Epidemic Empire, Anjuli Fatima Raza Kolb shows that this trope began in responses to the Indian Mutiny of 1857 and tracks its tenacious hold through 9/11 and beyond. The result is the first book-length study to approach the global War on Terror from a postcolonial literary perspective. Raza Kolb assembles a diverse archive from colonial India, imperial Britain, French and independent Algeria, the postcolonial Islamic diaspora, and the neoimperial United States. Anchoring her book are studies of four major writers in the colonial-postcolonial canon: Rudyard Kipling, Bram Stoker, Albert Camus, and Salman Rushdie. Across these sources, she reveals the tendency to imagine anticolonial rebellion, and Muslim insurgency specifically, as a virulent form of social contagion. Exposing the long history of this broken but persistent narrative, Epidemic Empire is a major contribution to the rhetorical history of our present moment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aDiseases in literature. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aImperialism. 0aLiterature, Moderny19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitical violence. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aTerrorism in literature. 0aTerrorism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z978311075377608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226739496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226739496.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  UChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075412-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishb2021  aG